(43, 9, 29, 12, 9, 11, 11, 'we know not from whence he is', 'Recognition of Divine Communication', 'Both passages emphasize the uncertainty surrounding the identity of a figure. In John 9:29, the speaker expresses ignorance about the origins of Jesus, while in 2 Kings 9:11, Jehu''s identity is questioned, highlighting a similar theme of recognition and misunderstanding.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 29, 19, 22, 6, 6, 'we know not from whence he is', 'Connection of Reproach and Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being despised and rejected. In John 9:29, the speaker expresses ignorance about the origins of Jesus, paralleling the humiliation expressed in Psalms 22:6, where the speaker feels like a reproach and is despised.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 30, 43, 12, 37, 37, 'he hath opened mine eyes', 'Miracles and Unbelief', 'This connection highlights the theme of miracles and the response of disbelief. In both passages, the miraculous acts of Jesus are acknowledged, yet they lead to a lack of belief among the people.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 30, 19, 119, 18, 18, 'opened mine eyes', 'Connection of Eye Opening', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of opening eyes to perceive wonders. In John 9:30, the man marvels at his sight being restored, while Psalms 119:18 requests divine help to see wondrous things in the law.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 30, 23, 29, 18, 18, 'opened mine eyes', 'Blindness and Sight', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of blindness and sight. John 9:30 speaks of the man receiving sight, while Isaiah 29:18 mentions the eyes of the blind seeing, linking the miraculous opening of eyes to spiritual enlightenment.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 30, 43, 3, 10, 10, NULL, 'Knowledge of Spiritual Truths', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual blindness among those who should know better. Both passages emphasize the surprising lack of understanding from individuals expected to possess knowledge about Jesus and His works.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 30, 23, 35, 5, 5, 'opened mine eyes', 'Healing of the Blind', 'Both passages emphasize the opening of blind eyes, highlighting miraculous healing. John 9:30 reflects the astonishment at the healing, while Isaiah 35:5 prophesies the restoration of sight.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 30, 40, 11, 5, 5, 'opened mine eyes', 'Healing and Sight Restoration', 'Both passages emphasize the restoration of sight, highlighting miraculous acts of healing. John 9:30 focuses on the opening of eyes, while Matthew 11:5 mentions the blind receiving their sight as part of Jesus'' ministry.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 30, 42, 7, 22, 22, NULL, 'Healing and Recognition of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the miraculous acts of Jesus, particularly the healing of the blind. In John 9:30, the healed man acknowledges the marvel of his sight, while in Luke 7:22, Jesus highlights the healing of the blind as a sign of his messianic mission.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 31, 20, 15, 29, 29, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Hearing', 'Both passages emphasize that God hears the prayers of the righteous while being distant from the wicked. This connection highlights the theme of God''s responsiveness to those who do His will.', 'theme', 0.622, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 31, 23, 1, 15, 15, 'God heareth not sinners', 'God''s Response to Sinners', 'Both passages emphasize that God does not hear those who are sinful or whose hands are full of blood. This connection highlights the theme of divine silence towards unrepentant individuals and the necessity of righteousness for God to listen.', 'theme', 0.5309999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 31, 20, 28, 9, 9, 'doeth his will', 'Connection of Prayer and Obedience', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of obedience to God for effective prayer. John 9:31 states that God hears those who do His will, while Proverbs 28:9 indicates that turning away from the law makes prayer an abomination.', 'theme', 0.517, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 31, 33, 3, 4, 4, 'God heareth not sinners', 'Divine Response to Behavior', 'Both passages emphasize that God does not hear those who behave poorly or sin. John 9:31 states that God hears worshippers who do His will, while Micah 3:4 indicates that God will not hear those who have behaved ill.', 'theme', 0.482, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 31, 19, 145, 19, 19, 'heareth not sinners', 'Connection of Divine Hearing', 'Both passages emphasize that God hears those who worship Him and do His will. John 9:31 states that God hears worshippers, while Psalms 145:19 affirms He hears the cries of those who fear Him.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 31, 38, 7, 13, 13, 'God heareth not sinners', 'Hearing and Response to God', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s response to those who seek Him. Both passages emphasize that God does not hear those who do not align with His will, indicating a reciprocal relationship between divine hearing and human obedience.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 31, 19, 34, 15, 16, 'God heareth not sinners', 'Connection of Divine Hearing', 'Both passages emphasize that God hears the cries of the righteous while turning away from evildoers. This connection highlights the theme of divine attention based on moral conduct.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 32, 23, 64, 4, 4, 'opened the eyes of one that was born blind', 'Connection of Sight and Hearing', 'This connection highlights the theme of perception and revelation. Both passages emphasize the limitations of human experience in understanding divine acts, particularly regarding sight and hearing.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 32, 18, 20, 4, 4, 'since the world began', 'Connection of Blindness and Knowledge', 'This connection highlights the theme of understanding and revelation. Both passages emphasize the significance of knowledge since the beginning of time, linking the miraculous act of opening blind eyes to a deeper understanding of human existence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 32, 42, 1, 70, 70, 'since the world began', 'Connection of Divine Action', 'Both passages emphasize actions that have occurred since the world began. John 9:32 highlights a miraculous event, while Luke 1:70 refers to prophetic speech throughout history.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 32, 66, 16, 18, 18, NULL, 'Miraculous Events and Their Impact', 'This connection highlights the extraordinary nature of events described in both passages. John 9:32 speaks of a miraculous healing, while Revelation 16:18 describes a cataclysmic earthquake, emphasizing significant occurrences that have not been seen before.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 33, 43, 9, 16, 16, NULL, 'Divine Authority and Miracles', 'Both passages emphasize the idea that a true man of God can perform miracles. John 9:33 asserts that if someone is not of God, they cannot do anything, while John 9:16 presents a division over whether Jesus, who performs miracles, can be a sinner. This connection highlights the debate over Jesus'' divine authority.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 33, 43, 3, 2, 2, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Authority', 'Both passages emphasize that miraculous acts are evidence of being sent from God. John 9:33 states that a man from God can do nothing without divine support, while John 3:2 affirms that Jesus'' miracles indicate he is a teacher from God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 33, 44, 5, 38, 39, 'if this man were not of God', 'Divine Authority in Actions', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority in both passages. John 9:33 asserts that actions of God cannot be denied, while Acts 5:38-39 emphasizes that if a work is of God, it cannot be overthrown.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 34, 43, 9, 2, 2, 'born in sins', 'Sin and Blindness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of sin in relation to blindness. In John 9:2, the disciples question whether the man''s blindness is due to his own sin or that of his parents, while in John 9:34, the response to the healed man implies he is considered sinful for his condition.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 34, 43, 9, 22, 22, 'cast him out', 'Fear of Exclusion from Synagogue', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of being cast out. In John 9:22, the parents fear expulsion for confessing Christ, while in John 9:34, the healed man is cast out for his testimony. This connection highlights the consequences of faith in the face of societal pressure.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 34, 23, 66, 5, 5, NULL, 'Rejection for Faithfulness', 'This connection highlights the theme of being cast out for faithfulness to God. Both passages depict individuals who are rejected or cast out for their beliefs, emphasizing the struggle faced by the faithful.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 34, 1, 19, 9, 9, 'dost thou teach us?', 'Rejection of Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection faced by those who challenge the status quo. In both passages, individuals are dismissed and threatened for their perceived judgment or teachings, illustrating a common response to those who speak out against wrongdoing.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 34, 18, 25, 4, 4, 'born in sins', 'Connection of Sin and Justification', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''born in sins'' and the challenge of justification before God. Job questions how one can be justified, while the response in John reflects the belief that the man was born sinful, leading to his rejection.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 34, 19, 51, 5, 5, 'born in sins', 'Connection of Sin and Birth', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being born in sin. John 9:34 reflects the belief that the man was born in sin, while Psalms 51:5 states that he was shapen in iniquity.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 34, 42, 18, 17, 17, 'born in sins', 'Childlike Faith and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment and humility. In John 9:34, the blind man''s perceived sinfulness leads to his rejection, while Luke 18:17 emphasizes the necessity of receiving the kingdom with childlike humility, contrasting the judgmental attitude of the Pharisees.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
